225
00:11:50,777 --> 00:11:54,111
I do, I do, but I also know that it
means different things to different people.

226
00:11:54,881 --> 00:11:56,816
Well, at Baptist, they
understand dizzy.

227
00:11:57,383 --> 00:11:59,375
That may be true, but
here in New Amsterdam,

228
00:11:59,452 --> 00:12:02,547
I want you to think about what
exactly "dizzy" means to you.

229
00:12:03,590 --> 00:12:06,424
It means "dizzy."

230
00:12:07,627 --> 00:12:10,597
The good news is that
your CT scans are negative

231
00:12:10,663 --> 00:12:12,223
and preliminary
lab tests all look fine.

232
00:12:13,266 --> 00:12:16,395
She's a good
doctor. Yes, she is.

233
00:12:17,003 --> 00:12:18,904
So, while I examine
my other patients,

234
00:12:18,972 --> 00:12:22,500
I want you to think
about your kind of dizzy.

235
00:12:27,113 --> 00:12:28,633
Tell me you're
admitting "dizzy chick."

236
00:12:28,815 --> 00:12:31,250
I cannot admit anyone
without a proper diagnosis,

237
00:12:31,517 --> 00:12:33,179
and I don't have any yet.

238
00:12:35,755 --> 00:12:37,399
Maybe we should make it
a multiple-choice question.

239
00:12:37,423 --> 00:12:40,484
We cannot give her choices.
It will influence her answers.

240
00:12:40,593 --> 00:12:43,188
We just need to know
what "dizzy" means to her,

