00:27:22,508 --> 00:27:25,478
Hey. Are those facts
or those feelings?

486
00:27:27,679 --> 00:27:28,703
It's feelings.

487
00:27:28,981 --> 00:27:32,349
Right, they're feelings, so why
don't we try sticking to the facts?

488
00:27:32,918 --> 00:27:34,648
Okay, I'll make
some phone calls.

489
00:27:35,521 --> 00:27:37,251
We're gonna get you
the home you deserve.

490
00:27:38,490 --> 00:27:39,514
I promise.

491
00:27:41,660 --> 00:27:42,684
All right.

492
00:28:03,382 --> 00:28:04,406
Dr. Frome?

493
00:28:12,191 --> 00:28:13,625
Don't we have
wheelchairs for that?

494
00:28:13,725 --> 00:28:16,752
They're all taken, but don't need one.
This is how we did it in Afghanistan.

495
00:28:16,862 --> 00:28:18,922
My man right here's
on his way to X-ray.

496
00:28:19,031 --> 00:28:21,262
Got a lateral malleolus
fracture playing indoor soccer,

497
00:28:21,366 --> 00:28:22,846
but he's gonna be
fine. Right, Camden?

498
00:28:23,202 --> 00:28:26,798
Did you take my
ibuprofen? Yeah. Thanks.

499
00:28:34,880 --> 00:28:36,974
Ah, Dr. Kapoor. Oh, Dean.

500
00:28:38,383 --> 00:28:41,285
Mrs. Monaghan has been
telling me a very interesting story.

501
00:28:41,787 --> 00:28:44,882
How you don't seem to
understand the word "dizzy."

502
00:28:46,892 --> 00:28:48,884
I do understand. Do you?

503
00:28:49,328 --> 00:28:50,762
Do you see what I mean?

504
00:28:50,829 --> 00:28:53,060
I should have walked
out of here an hour ago.

505
00:28:53,498 --> 00:28:54,557
Why didn't you?

506
00:28:54,900 --> 00:28:56,801
Because when I try to stand up,

507
00:28:56,902 --> 00:28:58,803
I feel like I'm
going to fall over.

508
00:28:58,904 --> 00:29:00,463
Like my feet aren't even there.

509
00:29:03,609 --> 00:29:06,738
Mrs. Monaghan, you have
Guillain-Barre syndrome.

510
00:29:07,312 --> 00:29:08,336
Excuse me?

511
00:29:08,647 --> 00:29:10,775
The anti-bodies your
system made to fight your cold

512
00:29:10,983 --> 00:29:12,679
are attacking the
nerves in your feet.

513
00:29:12,784 --> 00:29:14,024
That's why you can't feel them.

514
00:29:17,089 --> 00:29:19,854
I can now officially admit
you and get you taken care of.

515
00:29:25,530 --> 00:29:28,329
Help! We... We need help!

516
00:29:30,202 --> 00:29:33,468
Max... Max... Max
said he would help him.

517
00:29:33,538 --> 00:29:34,767
Max? Max?

518
00:29:35,140 --> 00:29:36,451
We've got an arterial bleed.

519
00:29:36,475 --> 00:29:37,704
Ready an intubation tray

520
00:29:37,809 --> 00:29:39,801
and page Max to Trauma One, now!

521
00:29:39,878 --> 00:29:42,177
Max! Come on, stay
with us. Come on.

522
00:29:47,552 --> 00:29:49,312
Class-one airway. Get
20 milligrams Etomidate

523
00:29:49,354 --> 00:29:52,290
and 100 milligrams succinylcholine
and let's start a propofol drip.

524
00:29:56,194 --> 00:29:57,628
Give me a 7.5 on
the hockey stick.

525
00:29:58,730 --> 00:30:00,450
Seven point five
on the hockey stick.

526
00:30:07,806 --> 00:30:08,830
I'm in.

527
00:30:22,587 --> 00:30:24,317
Now we find the bleeder.

528
00:30:34,266 --> 00:30:35,495
There it is.

529
00:30:35,701 --> 00:30:37,381
The bleeding's coming
from that bronchiole.

530
00:30:38,904 --> 00:30:40,566
Don't say it.

531
00:30:41,340 --> 00:30:42,774
We need Reynolds.

532
00:30:46,244 --> 00:30:48,042
Ah. Elbow deep
in a tricky closure.

533
00:30:48,113 --> 00:30:49,411
A man's bleeding out in the ED.

534
00:30:50,115 --> 00:30:51,592
Is this your idea of
relieving pressure?

535
00:30:51,616 --> 00:30:53,561
I know, Floyd. I'm sorry. I
don't know what else to do.

536
00:30:53,585 --> 00:30:54,696
I don't know who else to ask.

537
00:30:54,720 --> 00:30:56,240
Well, I can't be in
two places at once.

538
00:30:56,388 --> 00:30:59,085
Well, I hope you can figure out
how, or someone is going to die.

539
00:31:07,799 --> 00:31:10,064
Thank you. - Clamp.

540
00:31:14,806 --> 00:31:15,950
Blood pressure's dropping.

541
00:31:15,974 --> 00:31:17,033
Push more fluid.

542
00:31:17,209 --> 00:31:19,576
Got two liters open
wide. It's not enough.

543
00:31:19,778 --> 00:31:21,940
Grab a bag of O-negative
out of the trauma fridge.

544
00:31:22,481 --> 00:31:24,125
There's too much blood.
I can't see anything.

545
00:31:24,149 --> 00:31:27,142
There's a pumper in there
somewhere. I just can't find it. Suction.

546
00:31:29,488 --> 00:31:32,287
Will you get the Richardson
and lift up the middle lobe, please?

547
00:31:34,593 --> 00:31:36,323
There it is. I got that bad boy.

548
00:31:36,428 --> 00:31:38,428
Hey, Max, can you give
me a little light over here?

549
00:31:40,999 --> 00:31:42,239
There we go. NURSE: It's ready.

550
00:31:46,238 --> 00:31:47,433
Bleeding's stopped.

551
00:31:49,007 --> 00:31:52,444
Heart rate's steady.
Oxygenation stabilizing.

552
00:31:53,845 --> 00:31:55,279
Nice work, boys.

553
00:31:57,082 --> 00:32:00,280
So, what, you just let Dr. Fernandez
just bleed out in the OR?

554
00:32:00,952 --> 00:32:03,786
I left him in the hands
of a top-notch surgeon.

555
00:32:10,929 --> 00:32:12,795
One more running suture.

556
00:32:13,532 --> 00:32:14,852
Respiration is spontaneous.

557
00:32:16,835 --> 00:32:19,100
- That should hold.
- All right!

558
00:32:42,027 --> 00:32:44,155
Surgeons landed
at JFK an hour ago.

559
00:32:44,229 --> 00:32:45,720
Baptist is up and running.

560
00:32:46,398 --> 00:32:47,730
You did it, Max.

561
00:32:48,400 --> 00:32:51,370
It was fun, being
back in the trenches.

562
00:32:53,238 --> 00:32:54,297
And, Max...

563
00:32:56,141 --> 00:32:58,007
Don't ever do that again.

564
00:33:06,184 --> 00:33:09,177
Good news. Vance will
be in the ICU a few days,

565
00:33:09,254 --> 00:33:12,656
then a course of pills, then
he should make a full recovery.

566
00:33:12,924 --> 00:33:14,222
What was wrong with him?

567
00:33:14,326 --> 00:33:18,491
Histoplasmosis. It's a fungal
infection we see in the soil around Ohio.

568
00:33:18,563 --> 00:33:21,192
Must have been dormant
in Vance his whole life,

569
00:33:21,266 --> 00:33:23,826
and I'm sure living on the streets
weakened his immune system.

570
00:33:24,236 --> 00:33:26,603
The fungus reemerged, and
attacked his lungs and his liver.

571
00:33:26,938 --> 00:33:28,998
I would like to test
you both as well.

572
00:33:29,241 --> 00:33:32,370
We can't possibly
pay for all this.

573
00:33:32,577 --> 00:33:36,173
You don't have to. This is
why public hospitals exist.

574
00:33:36,748 --> 00:33:40,116
This is why I work here. This is
why all these doctors work here.

575
00:33:41,553 --> 00:33:42,851
We don't say no to anyone.

576
00:33:44,589 --> 00:33:45,613
We don't know how.

577
00:33:53,231 --> 00:33:54,255
Thank you.

578
00:33:58,570 --> 00:34:00,971
Casey, hydrate. Why?

579
00:34:01,573 --> 00:34:04,805
Because water plays a vital
role in nearly every bodily function.

580
00:34:05,076 --> 00:34:06,442
Mmm.

581
00:34:06,545 --> 00:34:07,774
Ah, I needed that.

582
00:34:09,314 --> 00:34:11,283
My ibuprofen wasn't ibuprofen.

583
00:34:11,616 --> 00:34:12,640
It was Adderall.

584
00:34:14,152 --> 00:34:16,112
That explains why I
thought I was covered in lice.

585
00:34:16,154 --> 00:34:17,554
And my headache never went away.

586
00:34:18,056 --> 00:34:20,321
I have ADHD. Listen,
you don't have to...

587
00:34:20,425 --> 00:34:21,791
I've had it my whole life.

588
00:34:22,227 --> 00:34:24,822
Adderall got me through med
school, through my residency.

589
00:34:24,930 --> 00:34:26,570
I mean, I couldn't
do this job without it.

590
00:34:26,731 --> 00:34:28,757
So, why do you keep it
in an ibuprofen bottle?

591
00:34:31,570 --> 00:34:33,163
You're killing
yourself for this job.

592
00:34:33,271 --> 00:34:35,399
Everyone here is.

593
00:34:38,009 --> 00:34:39,602
Everyone looks sad.

594
00:34:42,514 --> 00:34:46,007
Sweetheart, your cancer is back.

595
00:34:53,358 --> 00:34:54,417
Tianna,

596
00:34:55,493 --> 00:34:57,086
you asked what it's
like when you die.

597
00:34:59,965 --> 00:35:02,491
I think that it's like this.

598
00:35:17,115 --> 00:35:18,139
Come.

599
00:35:32,063 --> 00:35:34,157
So, when it happens,

600
00:35:35,567 --> 00:35:38,196
you won't be able to
see your mum and dad,

601
00:35:39,504 --> 00:35:41,370
and they won't
be able to see you.

602
00:35:42,207 --> 00:35:44,506
But they will always be there.

603
00:35:50,348 --> 00:35:53,182
And I'll always be here?

604
00:35:54,819 --> 00:35:55,843
Yes.

605
00:35:57,555 --> 00:36:00,150
You'll never stop
thinking of each other.

606
00:36:01,993 --> 00:36:04,326
You'll never stop
talking to each other.

607
00:36:06,865 --> 00:36:09,528
You'll just be on a
different side of the room.

608
00:36:16,041 --> 00:36:19,068
Mommy, can you hear me?

609
00:36:20,512 --> 00:36:24,176
Yes, baby doll. We
can hear you, little one.

610
00:36:25,216 --> 00:36:26,548
I can hear you too.

611
00:36:55,613 --> 00:36:57,809
<i>Hello, my old heart</i>

612
00:36:58,216 --> 00:37:00,447
<i>How have you been?</i>

613
00:37:00,785 --> 00:37:04,278
<i>Are you still there
inside my chest?</i>

614
00:37:06,091 --> 00:37:08,492
<i>I've been so worried</i>

615
00:37:08,593 --> 00:37:14,624
<i>You've been so still,
barely beating at all</i>

616
00:37:17,569 --> 00:37:18,593
You okay?

617
00:37:19,104 --> 00:37:20,834
<i>Don't leave me here alone</i>

618
00:37:21,106 --> 00:37:23,473
<i>Don't tell me how we grow</i>

619
00:37:24,242 --> 00:37:25,767
I took the hard road.

620
00:37:28,513 --> 00:37:29,572
And?

621
00:37:32,183 --> 00:37:33,310
Better views.

622
00:37:33,418 --> 00:37:34,511
<i>I wanna find a home</i>

623
00:37:34,619 --> 00:37:37,145
<i>And I wanna share it with you</i>

624
00:37:47,465 --> 00:37:50,867
<i>Hello, my old heart</i>

625
00:38:15,894 --> 00:38:17,863
You know, my attending
wouldn't even let me look

626
00:38:17,962 --> 00:38:21,364
in the OR the first three
months of my residency?

627
00:38:21,466 --> 00:38:23,059
I can still hear him in my head.

628
00:38:23,568 --> 00:38:26,834
"Reynolds, you're more likely
to cut yourself than the patient."

629
00:38:28,640 --> 00:38:30,700
I don't know. Old
habits die hard, I guess.

630
00:38:31,643 --> 00:38:34,169
Well, the difference is
you trained these residents.

631
00:38:34,846 --> 00:38:38,544
Yeah, well, but, you know, if
something had gone wrong...

632
00:38:40,084 --> 00:38:43,543
Okay, do you know what feels
even better than being in control?

633
00:38:44,389 --> 00:38:45,550
Letting go of it.

634
00:39:06,211 --> 00:39:08,407
Don't start what
you can't finish.

635
00:39:15,520 --> 00:39:16,715
<i>Cold</i>

636
00:39:17,388 --> 00:39:22,258
Well, on the bright side, I
can finally take up fencing.

637
00:39:24,462 --> 00:39:26,761
<i>She glides away</i>

638
00:39:26,865 --> 00:39:29,266
In a few weeks, we'll
start chemo in the mornings

639
00:39:29,367 --> 00:39:31,029
and radiation at night.

640
00:39:31,102 --> 00:39:32,968
By "a few weeks,"
you mean... Two.

641
00:39:33,071 --> 00:39:34,596
'Cause sometimes
"a few" can mean...

642
00:39:34,706 --> 00:39:35,730
Two. Right.

643
00:39:35,807 --> 00:39:38,276
<i>Does she know that
we bleed the same?</i>

644
00:39:41,312 --> 00:39:43,042
There's so much to do.

645
00:39:43,414 --> 00:39:45,440
<i>Don't wanna cry,
but I break that way</i>

646
00:39:46,050 --> 00:39:47,916
You're gonna have to prioritize.

647
00:39:50,588 --> 00:39:52,284
You mean start saying no?

648
00:39:53,324 --> 00:39:55,259
I mean start saying yes.

649
00:39:57,962 --> 00:39:58,986
To you.

650
00:40:01,466 --> 00:40:03,094
What do you need, Max?

651
00:40:22,186 --> 00:40:23,518
<i>I</i>

652
00:40:23,955 --> 00:40:25,617
<i>Have got a fear</i>

653
00:40:27,792 --> 00:40:29,818
<i>Oh, in my blood</i>

654
00:40:32,130 --> 00:40:33,359
<i>Cold</i>

655
00:40:34,265 --> 00:40:35,494
<i>Sheets</i>

656
00:40:37,635 --> 00:40:39,695
<i>Oh, where's my love</i>

657
00:40:41,272 --> 00:40:43,138
<i>I am</i>

658
00:40:43,207 --> 00:40:44,937
<i>Searching high</i>

659
00:40:45,176 --> 00:40:46,804
<i>I'm searching low</i>

660
00:40:47,612 --> 00:40:48,773
<i>In the night</i>

661
00:40:50,014 --> 00:40:55,317
<i>Ooh, does she know
that we bleed the same?</i>

662
00:40:58,990 --> 00:41:04,554
<i>Ooh, don't want to
cry, but I break that way</i>

663
00:41:09,167 --> 00:41:12,331
<i>Did she run away,
did she run away?</i>

664
00:41:12,403 --> 00:41:15,862
<i>I don't know</i>

665
00:41:18,142 --> 00:41:21,635
<i>If she ran away, if she ran away</i>

666
00:41:21,713 --> 00:41:24,376
<i>Come back home</i>

667
00:41:32,490 --> 00:41:33,514
Max.

668
00:41:36,761 --> 00:41:37,820
Hey.

669
00:41:38,029 --> 00:41:40,191
It's 9:30. You're gonna be late.

670
00:41:42,166 --> 00:41:44,533
No, I'm not.

671
00:41:46,037 --> 00:41:48,597
Oh, my God. Did you get fired?

672
00:41:50,008 --> 00:41:51,840
That was fast, even for you.

673
00:41:53,344 --> 00:41:55,006
I'm taking the day off.

674
00:41:57,949 --> 00:41:59,918
Thought I'd spend the day here,

675
00:42:01,886 --> 00:42:03,013
with you.
